ce:section.ce:para:
FTIR and XPS spectra are applied to probe functional groups and the chemical composition of the as-synthesized Sc-CDs. As presented in FTIR spectra (Fig. 3a
                        ), the characteristic absorption peaks between 3200 and 3400 cm−1 correspond to the stretching vibration of O–H/N–H bonds [34], while a slight peak at 1768 cm−1 can be assigned to CO stretching vibrations [40]. Moreover, the peaks at 1473, 1373, 1213 and 1101 cm−1 are found, suggesting the existence of CN, –NO2, NH and at C–O–C bonds, respectively [36]. Noteworthy, an apparent peak associated with stretching vibration of CN band (i. e., Schiff base structure) at 1630 cm−1 
                        [35,36] substantiates the contribution of Schiff base reaction during the formation of Sc-CDs. XPS measurement testifies the conclusions from FTIR spectra. The full-scan XPS illustrates three typical peaks at 285, 532 and 399 eV, indicating the presence of C (76.93 %), O (12.77 %) and N (10.31 %), respectively (Fig. S2). The high-resolution C1s XPS illustrates the four fitting peaks: C–C/C=C (284.2 eV), C– N (285.4 eV), C–OH (286.3 eV) and C=N/C=O (288.3 eV) (Fig. 3b). In the O1s spectrum (Fig. 3c), two peaks are assigned to CO (530.2 eV) and CO (532.3 eV). And the N1s spectrum can be deconvoluted into three binding energy peaks related to CN (398.6 eV), NH (399.8 eV) and –NO2 (406.1 eV), respectively [36]. Notably, the CN bond takes the most proportion, further confirming that Sc-CDs possess a large number of Schiff base structures. To sum up, FTIR and XPS analyses substantially demonstrate that there are numerous O- and N-containing functional groups on the surfaces of Sc-CDs. And these groups endow Sc-CDs with the excellent hydrophilic property [35], laying a solid foundation for their application as a water-based corrosion inhibitor. Additionally, the production of Schiff base structures from Schiff base reaction during the preparation is expected to improve the corrosion inhibition effect of Sc-CDs.
